Introduction:

This data contains records of fitness-related data that analyzes the workout efficiency of the users based on many variables.

My motivation for this project is based on personal interest as one of my hobby is strength training and I’m in search of a workout that will increase my calorie burn.

Link: https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/adilshamim8/workout-and-fitness-tracker-data

Visual Analysis: Hexbin

With the use of hexbin plot, we can see the varying results of calories burned in correlation to duration. We can observe that there is no linear trend, meaning longer duration does not always mean higher calorie burn. Therefore if one want to burn calories in a short duration, they can choose a high intensity workout.

If we look at the HIIT graph, we can see that more users were able to loose about 900 calories in just 50 minutes. Compared to strength training, there is a less data input of users that lost the same about of calories within the same duration.

ggplot(fitness_tracker, aes(x = `Workout Duration (mins)`, y = `Calories Burned`)) +
  geom_hex(bins = 15) +
  scale_fill_viridis_c(option = "C", name = "Density") +
  facet_wrap(~ `Workout Type`) +  # Separate hexbin plots for each workout type
  labs(title = "Calories Burned vs Workout Duration by Workout Type",
       x = "Workout Duration (mins)",
       y = "Calories Burned") +
  theme_minimal()

Visual Analysis: Boxplot

This is a categorical vs quantitative plot. One observation I noticed is that this data set doesn’t have any outliers. Another is that the workout types have a similar median. It did surprise me that yoga is on the same average of calorie burn with all of these workouts because I didn’t know one can burn that much calorie with yoga workouts. But it probably also depend on the intensity.

ggplot(fitness_tracker, aes(x = `Workout Type`, y = `Calories Burned`, fill = `Workout Type`)) +
  geom_boxplot(alpha = 0.7) +
  labs(title = "Calories Burned by Workout Type",
       x = "Workout Type",
       y = "Calories Burned") +
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(legend.position = "none")

Dataset Manipulation: dplyr

This dataset shows the average heart rate per workout duration with the use of dplyr manipulation. This is another interesting finding to me because Yoga actually generated the highest average heart rate especially compared to HIIT.

# Data Manipulation: Calculate average heart rate per workout type
heart_rate_summary <- fitness_tracker %>%
  group_by(`Workout Type`) %>%
  summarize(avg_heart_rate = mean(`Heart Rate (bpm)`, na.rm = TRUE),
            avg_duration = mean(`Workout Duration (mins)`, na.rm = TRUE))

# Scatter plot: Average Heart Rate vs. Average Workout Duration
ggplot(heart_rate_summary, aes(x = avg_duration, y = avg_heart_rate, color = `Workout Type`)) +
  geom_point(size = 2) +
  geom_text(aes(label = `Workout Type`), vjust = -1) + # Add labels for readability
  labs(title = "Average Heart Rate vs. Workout Duration",
       x = "Average Workout Duration (mins)",
       y = "Average Heart Rate (bpm)") +
  theme_minimal()

Statistical Analysis: Two Quantitative Variables

Pearson

Null Hypothesis: There is no correlation between Heart Rate and Calories Burned.

Alternative Hypothesis: There is a correlation between Heart Rate and Calories Burned.

# Perform Pearson correlation test
pearson_bpm_cals <- cor.test(fitness_tracker$`Heart Rate (bpm)`, 
                             fitness_tracker$`Calories Burned`, 
                             method = "pearson", 
                             use = "complete.obs")

# Print the full result
print(pearson_bpm_cals)
## 
##  Pearson's product-moment correlation
## 
## data:  fitness_tracker$`Heart Rate (bpm)` and fitness_tracker$`Calories Burned`
## t = -0.65934, df = 9998, p-value = 0.5097
## alternative hypothesis: true correlation is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  -0.02619061  0.01300783
## sample estimates:
##          cor 
## -0.006593923
ggplot(fitness_tracker, aes(x = `Heart Rate (bpm)`, y = `Calories Burned`)) +
  geom_point(alpha = 0.5, color = "blue") +  # Scatter plot with transparency
  geom_smooth(method = "lm", color = "red", se = TRUE) +  # Linear regression line
  labs(title = "Correlation Between Heart Rate and Calories Burned",
       x = "Heart Rate (bpm)",
       y = "Calories Burned") +
  theme_minimal()
## `geom_smooth()` using formula = 'y ~ x'

Based on this Pearson Correlation Test, we failed to reject the null hypothesis since the p-value is greater than 0.05.Therefore, there is no statistically significant correlation between Heart Rate and Calories Burned.

The t-value suggests that we have a weak evidence of correlation.

Coefficient correlation is close to 0, meaning that there’s no significant relationship between the two variables.

T-test: Categorical vs. Quantitative

Null Hypothesis: There is no significant correlation between male and female calorie burn in high-intensity strength workouts.

Alternate Hypothesis: There is a significant correlation between male and female calorie burn in high-intensity strength workouts.

# Subset data for high-intensity strength workouts
high_intensity_strength <- subset(fitness_tracker, 
                                  `Workout Type` == "Strength" & 
                                    `Workout Intensity` == "High" & 
                                    Gender %in% c("Male", "Female"))

# Perform Welch's t-test
t_test_result <- t.test(`Calories Burned` ~ Gender, 
                        data = high_intensity_strength, 
                        var.equal = FALSE)

# Print result
print(t_test_result)
## 
##  Welch Two Sample t-test
## 
## data:  Calories Burned by Gender
## t = -2.1974, df = 373.36, p-value = 0.0286
## alternative hypothesis: true difference in means between group Female and group Male is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  -104.772111   -5.815183
## sample estimates:
## mean in group Female   mean in group Male 
##             522.9423             578.2360

We were able to reject the null hypothesis since the p-value is lower than 0.05, suggesting that there is a significant correlation between make and female calorie burn in high-intensity strength workouts.

The t value indicates that on average, women burn fewer calories than men during high-intensity workouts. We can also see the 55cal difference.
